@BreensR @ndiritu_michael @LinusMoose Nice! You won't regret trying it 🙂. If you do find anything you think should be improved please please let me know 🙏

@adjorno @PreusslerBerlin @jovchem @Zhuinden At least this was my understanding of what you wrote 😅. So in the end you'd have two unit tests to test the two classes in isolation. I would keep only one unit test testing only the behaviour I expect, regardless of it being achieved by two classes. The unit != the class.

@adjorno @PreusslerBerlin @jovchem @Zhuinden The scenario is: you have your class tested. Everything works but you realize your class is way too big. So you refactor your class into two. The second one just helps the first, it is an implementation detail of the first. In your view, you should also split the test, right?

@adjorno @PreusslerBerlin @jovchem @Zhuinden Even if they only change once, by forcing yourself to unit test each class in isolation, you already pay a significant cost with no actual benefits comparing to just testing the behavior. I'm pretty sure most code changes once, if not, why are we making SOFTware.

@adjorno @PreusslerBerlin @jovchem @Zhuinden Otherwise tests actually make refactoring and improving the code harder when one of the main reasons to have tests is to free you to confidently improve and refactor code. Stale code will rotten, so we need to be able to touch code and we need tests to do it with confidence.

@adjorno @PreusslerBerlin @jovchem @Zhuinden << and that test passes, then it means all collaborator classes are also working as they should.
